Electricity generation in Ghana has historically relied heavily on hydro and thermal sources. Nevertheless, there has been a deliberate shift towards incorporating more renewable energy sources over the past decade, driven by a desire to diversify the energy mix. Hydropower dominated electricity generation in Ghana from 2000 to 2015, with its share ranging between 51% and 92%. Thermal power has, since 2016, dominated electricity generation, with output steadily increasing and peaking at 14,930 GWh in 2023 before a slight decline to 14,524 GWh in 2024.



